reviews.review_text:
JFK was eventual but took Dylan
The second of the dates with Dylan (after skipping a week), and a rare non-Spectrum, outdoor appearance in Philly. Also, the best of the six shows. The Dead played an over-2hr set before backing Dylan. It's one of the more amazing single set lists: Althea, then a Cassidy>China>Rider and a Terrapin? Along with a best-of example of Esau? Shit, man. This 90k-seater was one of the largest stadia played in the 30 years. It had the most tickets sold of the six shows - even though it was the one that didn't sell out [if Big A didn't sell out, it was very close]. A set of hot Dead during the Dylan-galvanized hot streak. Iko Iko solidly introduces the non-Heads to Deadercise. An exciting Jack Straw then introduces X factor. Dig this Sugaree. Sometimes you could tell that they knew they were playing hot; and sometimes that they know that we know that they know. Minglewood (Philly fillies [natch]/T in Philly) has Bobby's Slide Practice™, but also roaring Jer, and all is right with the universe. A crisp, perfected Althea; and then Bobby's current fave Brother Esau (which had just been released as a B-side), in an idealized version. The "take a step back" includes a Mexican Hat Dance and a Shave and a Haircut. Push Comes to Shove is also in its peak version, here with alt lyrics "are you still in dread/scratching at the window/rapping at the door". The zenith continues with an ace Cassidy and a good China Cat into a blow-out Rider. You'll probably expect a tight, roaring Terrapin instead of this flat version (Phil adds the best parts). But past the generic Drums>Space it's solid GOGD; tight like all of summer '87. They return for Touch of Grey - sans Dylan, unlike other encores from the pairing. Just okay, it improves, by virtue of Phil and the drummers. Overall = B+    4½ stars   HG Highlights: Jack Straw - exciting Sugaree - they knew that we knew New Minglewood Blues - roaring Jer & T in Philly Althea - crisp My Brother Esau - idealized version When Push Comes to Shove - its peak Cassidy - ensemble tightness I Know You Rider - and China coming in SOURCES: The 149955_UltraMatrix is the updated SBD; a remaster of miller_101651, with complete tunings. It needs BAL intervention and EQ [boosting lowest and highest]. The 149959_sbd is the feed to the vid truck (screens), without a Healey mic matrix applied, but is mono. The 135276_mtx_tobin is a lively tape matrix. The Dylan SBDs are rare (unknown_97490 is just his set) - per his rules these were no-taping shows, and almost all boots of Dylan from this tour are AUD. The great Tobin vid is on YouTube, and there's a Dylan vid out there, too.
beautiful night was there . and it was wonderful. caught 4-5 shows that summer tour.
